<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="367" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,152,719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,152,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini, 2019" authorityName="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini" authorityYear="2019" box="[343,611,153,179]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="primus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[343,611,153,179]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Simothraulopsis primus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[619,709,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[619,709,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
has a body color pattern and equally divergent inner margins of penis lobes similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lima, 2018" authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" box="[398,664,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuosus">
<emphasis box="[398,523,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. sinuosus</emphasis>
Lima, 2018
</taxonomicName>
. The penis projection is short, lanceolate, and narrowing towards the apex, similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Nascimento, Salles &amp; Hamada, 2017" authorityName="Nascimento, Salles &amp; Hamada" authorityYear="2017" box="[416,992,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inaequalis">
<emphasis box="[416,562,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. inaequalis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Nascimento, J. M. C. &amp; Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N." box="[570,992,225,251]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" pagination="1 - 81" refId="ref2834" refString="Nascimento, J. M. C., Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N. (2017) Systematics of Simothraulopsis Demoulin, 1966 (Ephemeroptera: Leptophlebiidae). Zootaxa, 4285 (1), 1 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4285.1.1" type="journal article" year="2017">Nascimento, Salles &amp; Hamada, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName authority="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini, 2019" authorityName="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini" authorityYear="2019" box="[1120,1227,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="primus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1120,1227,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. primus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1235,1325,225,251]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1235,1325,225,251]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is clearly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" box="[369,493,261,287]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuosus">
<emphasis box="[369,493,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. sinuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shapes of penis projections; these are long, spine-like and sinuous in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. sinuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and they are short, lanceolate, and straight in 
<taxonomicName authority="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini, 2019" authorityName="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini" authorityYear="2019" box="[729,835,297,323]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="primus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[729,835,297,323]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. primus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[843,933,297,323]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[843,933,297,323]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Furthermore, the new species can be clearly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nascimento, Salles &amp; Hamada" authorityYear="2017" box="[371,517,333,359]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inaequalis">
<emphasis box="[371,517,333,359]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. inaequalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a brown thorax, a yellowish brown abdomen, the apical lower portion of the hind wing tinged with brown, and the “U” shape between the penis lobes. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nascimento, Salles &amp; Hamada" authorityYear="2017" box="[1210,1356,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inaequalis">
<emphasis box="[1210,1356,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. inaequalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an orangish color, tergum VIII with a submedial black mark near the posterior margin, almost the entire lower portion of the hind wing black, and a “V” shape between the penis lobes. Beyond morphogical differences, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" box="[1312,1436,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuosus">
<emphasis box="[1312,1436,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. sinuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurrence area is restricted to the state of 
<collectingRegion box="[645,705,477,503]" country="Brazil" name="Piaui" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Piauí</collectingRegion>
, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nascimento, Salles &amp; Hamada" authorityYear="2017" box="[790,937,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inaequalis">
<emphasis box="[790,937,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. inaequalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be found in 
<collectingRegion box="[1133,1183,477,503]" country="Suriname" name="Para" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Pará</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1240,1358,477,503]" country="Venezuela" name="Amazonas" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
states. The only record of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Demoulin" authorityYear="1966" box="[481,663,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[481,663,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">Simothraulopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the studied area belongs to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Traver, 1947)" authorityName="Traver" authorityYear="1947" baseAuthorityName="Traver" baseAuthorityYear="1947" box="[1004,1312,513,539]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="demerara">
<emphasis box="[1004,1141,513,539]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. demerara</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Traver, J. R." box="[1156,1304,513,539]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" pagination="149 - 160" refId="ref3026" refString="Traver, J. R. (1947) Notes on Neotropical mayflies. Part II. Family Baetidae, subfamily Leptophlebiinae. Revista de Entomologia, 18, 149 - 160." type="journal article" year="1947">Traver, 1947</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, which has a wide distribution, present mainly in the north and northeast region, but it differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini, 2019" authorityName="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini" authorityYear="2019" box="[1140,1246,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="primus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1140,1246,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. primus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1254,1344,549,575]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1254,1344,549,575]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
by having the thorax orangish brown, the abdomen grayish brown, the costal region and almost the entire lower portion of the hind wing black, and by the “V” shape between the penis lobes. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini, 2019" authorityName="Orlando &amp; Krolow &amp; Boldrini" authorityYear="2019" box="[989,1096,621,647]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="primus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[989,1096,621,647]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">S. primus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1103,1194,621,647]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1103,1194,621,647]" pageId="4" pageNumber="367" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the thorax is brown; the abdomen is yellowish brown; the apical lower portion of the hind wing is tinged with brown; and there is a “U” shape between the penis lobes.
</paragraph>
